cerns as the need to restore joy and dignity to work in modem industry.Originally published in 1978.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aDecorative artsxGermany. 0aDecorative artszGermany. 7aART / Folk & Outsider Art.2bisacsh  aADAPT.  aAdolf Hitler.  aAdolf Loos.  aAdolf Ziegler.  aAdolf.  aAdvanced capitalism.  aAestheticism.  aAlbert Speer.  aAnti-communism.  aAntimilitarism.  aApplied arts.  aArt Nouveau.  aArthur Moeller van den Bruck.  aArts and Crafts movement.  aAugust Endell.  aBaedeker.  aBaghdad Railway.  aBauhaus.  aBruno Taut.  aCultural Bolshevism.  aCultural hegemony.  aCultural policy.  aCulture and Society.  aDada.  aDemagogue.  aDesigner.  aDeutscher Werkbund.  aDeutsches Museum.  aEnabling act.  aErich Mendelsohn.  aErnst May.  aFolk art.  aFriedrich Meinecke.  aFriedrich Naumann.  aFritz Schumacher (architect).  aFritz Todt.  aGerman art.  aGleichschaltung.  aGreat Leap Forward.  aGropius.  aHandicraft.  aHans Poelzig.  aHeimatschutz.  aHenry van de Velde.  aHermann Muthesius.  aImperialism.  aIndividualism.  aInside the Third Reich.  aKampfbund.  aKonrad Adenauer.  aKritik.  aKäthe Kollwitz.  aLudwig Gies.  aManifesto.  aMass production.  aMax Scheler.  aMeistersinger. 